   abstract = {In this paper, I address shortcomings in psychology's attempts at engaging with environmentalism, and provide a theoretical foundation from which psychologists can be more ecologically aware and contribute toward environmental and conservational efforts. I draw from feminist epistemology, and more specifically, ecofeminism, for nuanced and holistic ways to think about our place in, and ethical responsibility to the environment. Ecofeminism provides the necessary conditions for an ethical ecology that can translate into a theoretical groundwork for ecopsychology. I also discuss the ontological implications in a human/nature relationship, and make some suggestions for a causal theory of relational ontology for ethical ecology. In proposing a theoretical foundation for ecopsychology I am synthesizing ecofeminist epistemologies, relational ontology, and holistic perspectives on the human/nature relationship. Nature is here defined as the physical environment, including constructed and natural habitats, and all living organisms.},
